individually held opinions, but is fundamentally a public concept, formed through interaction in conversations and with prevailing attitudes and ideas “in the air.” In Group Experiment, edited by Friedrich Pollock, they published their findings on their group discussion experiments that delved deeper into the process of opinion formation. Andrew J. Perrin and Jeffrey K. Olick make a case that these experiments are an important missing link in the ontology and methodology of current social-science survey research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAdorno, Theodor W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdorno, Theodor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBöhm, Franz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlick, Jeffrey K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerrin, Andrew J, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPerrin, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067427690140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674276901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674276901/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK